 "components": {
  "instruction": "Classify the given text into one of these categories: alarm_query, alarm_set, calendar_query, calendar_remove, calendar_set, cooking_recipe, datetime_query, email_query, email_sendemail, general_quirky, iot_hue_lightoff, lists_createoradd, lists_query, lists_remove, music_query, news_query, play_audiobook, play_music, play_podcasts, play_radio, qa_currency, qa_definition, qa_factoid, qa_stock, recommendation_events, recommendation_locations, social_post, takeaway_order, transport_query, weather_query.\n\nImportant classification rules:\n- The phrase \"repeat birthday\" should be classified as 'calendar_set' (not 'calendar_query'), as it indicates setting up a recurring calendar event rather than querying about an existing one.\n- Distinguish carefully between queries (asking for information) and action commands (setting, creating, or modifying something):\n  - Queries typically ask about existing information (e.g., \"when is...\", \"what...\", \"show me...\")\n  - Set/create commands indicate creating or modifying entries (e.g., \"repeat...\", \"set...\", \"add...\", \"create...\")\n- For calendar-related inputs:\n  - Use 'calendar_set' for creating new events or setting up recurring events\n  - Use 'calendar_query' for asking about existing calendar entries\n  - Use 'calendar_remove' for deleting calendar entries\n\nAdditional critical rules:\n- **Reminders about meetings, events, or appointments should be classified as 'calendar_set', NOT 'alarm_set'**\n  - Alarms are for time-based alerts (e.g., \"wake me up at 7am\", \"set alarm for 6pm\")\n  - Calendar/reminders are for event-based notifications about activities, tasks, meetings, or things to remember\n  - Keywords like \"remind\", \"reminder\", \"meeting\", \"appointment\", \"event\" typically indicate 'calendar_set'\n  - Even complex phrasing like \"remind yourself to remind me about...\" should be classified as 'calendar_set' when it involves meetings or events\n- Use 'alarm_set' only for simple time-based wake-up calls or alerts without specific event context\n- Use 'calendar_set' for all reminder requests related to meetings, appointments, tasks, or events"
 },
